english:
  title: On the Name Zixu
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Park of Jeongje was the top graduate of the state examination in the year Imyn of Goryeo. Possessing a rectified and cautious nature, with learning both precise and expansive, he became the standard-bearer of officials in his time. His original name was Sil, and his courtesy name was Zixu, though he later changed his name to Uijung while keeping his courtesy name unchanged. Once he said to me, "I once took the teaching from the Analects that 'even Confucius seemed empty' and made it my name and courtesy name. Later I changed my name, but kept my courtesy name the same. Please record the meaning of this for my descendants." Though I demurred out of my own insufficiency, I could not refuse, and spoke thus:

    In the learning of the gentleman, virtue seeks to become substantial, yet the mind seeks to remain humble. Emptiness is the very essence of my mind, wherein all principles inhere. Thus whoever wishes to rectify the heart must first make it empty, and only then will selfish desire not linger and the Way of Heaven remain eternally present. Similarly, whoever walks the path must first empty the heart, and only then will arrogance and stinginess not arise while one's virtue grows more exalted. Therefore, emptiness is the root of substance.

    This is why the Master in his former name already took this principle upon himself as a self-admonition. Yet when the gentleman pursues learning, it is for the sake of applying it to affairs. To apply it to affairs without losing what is timely and fitting—this belongs solely to the Mean. From the governance of Yao, Shun, Tang, and Wu above, to the transmission of the Way by Confucius, Yan Hui, Zisi, and Mencius below—all accomplished this through the Mean. This Mean has both substance and function. When yet unarrisen, by perfecting emptiness we preserve the body unmoved by any partiality, and then when action arises it accords with measure, so the function remains free from excess or deficiency. Thus emptiness is also the substance of the Mean.

    This is why the Master in his latter name likewise took this principle upon himself as a further admonition. Observing the sequence of his advancement in virtue and cultivation of conduct, his illumination of substance and refinement of function—from his names alone one may discern the effort he pours forth. Because the Master's learning focused wholly on inward cultivation, his practice grew ever more exacting without ever satisfying himself, and his accumulation grew ever more full without ever content. In the ordinary patterns of human relations and daily affairs, in the midst of movement and stillness, word and silence, and even through hardship and calamity, in all his conduct he ever sought to accord with what was fitting and timely. Thus he became top graduate of the great examination, rose through distinguished posts, and ascended even to the chancellor's seat, yet his bearing showed no arrogance. Sent on embassy during wartime, he was detained in enemy lands with death hovering at every moment, yet his resolve never wavered. At last, through his gift of eloquent response, he preserved our borders intact, achieving great merit. Yet he then withdrew, living in simplicity, maintaining frugality as if he were but a poor scholar. This stemmed from his heart being empty yet centered, whereby his virtue became full yet constant. Thus all that manifested in his conduct accorded with the fitness of circumstance, achieving such excellence.

    In former days when the Master served as lecturer at the National Academy, I began my studies under his guidance. From that time, following him as his student for decades, I knew him most intimately. Therefore I have written this account of his learning and achievements to serve as this explanation of his name, not from any wish to flatter, but from genuine understanding. Autumn, eighth month, in the third year of Jianwen.
  footnotes:
    - Zixu (子虛) derives from the Analects, where Confucius is described as seemingly empty or unassuming.
    - The name Uijung (宜中) combines the concepts of 'timeliness' (宜) and 'the Mean' (中), both central to Neo-Confucian philosophy.
    - Kwon Geun served both Goryeo and the early Joseon dynasty, experiencing capture during military conflicts.
    - The National Academy (成均館) was the highest educational institution of Goryeo and early Joseon.
    - Jianwen era refers to the early Ming period; this was written when Kwon Geun was serving at the Ming court.
